 Certify that the hives from which the honeybees in the shipment
were derived were individually inspected by an official of the
regulatory agency no more than 10 days prior to export;

 Certify that the hives from which the germ plasm in each shipment
was derived were individually inspected by an official of the
regulatory agency no more than 10 days prior to export;

 The U.S. port where you expect the shipment to arrive. The port
must be staffed by an APHIS inspector (see 

  § 

    322.11


);

 Proper documentation (see 

  § 

    322.6


);

 Identification of all bee parasites, including mites, that occur in
the exporting region but not in the United States or that are listed
as significant for international trade by the OIE;

Provide your signature and the date of your signature under the following certification: “I certify that all statements and entries I have made on this document are true and accurate to the best of my knowledge and belief. I understand that any intentional false statement or misrepresentation made on this document is a violation of law and punishable by a fine of not more than $10,000, or imprisonment of not more than 5 years, or both. (
18 U.S.C. 1001
).” If you are required to have a sponsor for your permit application, your sponsor must also sign and date under the same certification.

 The following materials are approved as packing materials:
Absorbent cotton or processed cotton padding free of cottonseed;
cages made of processed wood; cellulose materials; excelsior; felt;
ground peat (peat moss); paper or paper products; phenolic resin
foam; sawdust; sponge rubber; thread waste, twine, or cord; and
vermiculite.
